defaultPost the 2004 Disability and Development conference hosted by the World Bank, 
defaultdisability activists began to have a formal presence on the World Bank’s Disability and Development website.  Since then there has been a notable recognition how stigma works on 
defaultmany levels ranging from language practices and their work on the psyche to actual fu
defaultnding opportunities for PWD.  For example, as
default noted in an article by 
defaultFlavia Nakabuye Bwire, George Mukasa, 
defaultand 
defaultRoy Mersland
default (2009), notions of mainstreaming and inclusion 
defaultcannot work if there is not work on the social and cultural stigmas against PWD.  
defaultIn
default their study of a Ugandan microlending d
defaultevelopment initiative they show
default how despite the intentions of “mainstreaming” PWD into micro-lending programs, for example, prevaili
defaultng ideologies about PWD kept lenders from reaching out to this population.  Likewise, if they did, lenders tended to make special programs for PWD and in doing so privileged microlending plans that were unsustainable 
defaultfor the person taking the loan 
defaultonce the
default loan period ended. Notably, they found that many banks and 
defaultlending 
defaultNGOs chose not to lend to PWD because they believed the following: 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default[15] 
defaultAlong these same lines, because many microlending agencies rely upon solidarity groups or village banks, due to stigmatization, local community members also believed th
defaultese same stigmas and discouraged agencies from reaching out to PWD.  As Bwire et als
default (2009)
default, make clear in their findings, such stigmas not only limit important business opportunities for the wider community and the lending agency, they also “
defaultfail to pract
defaultice the double bottom line policy of reaching both financial and social objectives, which nearly all 
defaultmicro-finance agencies
default claim
default”
default 
defaultto be part of. 
defaultA contextual model of 
defaultdisability
default takes into account how mainstreaming and inclusion programs 
defaultmust address wide
defaultr contexts, such as addressing how a community talks about and makes presumptions about PWD within local contexts. 
defaultThe 
defaultUganda project 
