defaultDisability and development programs should
default[18] 
defaultMainstreaming and inclusion initiatives tend to emphasize the need for people disabilities to change themselves so that they can participate equally with peopl
defaulte who do not have disabilities.
default Such priorities place the onus for 
defaultPWD
default to develop skills and habits on par with their non-disabled community members.  And in most cases, due to physical or psychological barriers, people with disability are (like many who are marginalized) are unable to 
defaultparticipate in the mainstream on equal footing without significant changes to the environment and to ideologies and expectations about “normal” ways of being verses “abnormal” ways of being.  In some cases, programs that have only emphasized work or educat
defaultion related activities and microloans aimed to teach 
defaultPWD
default how to participate in the formal labor sector, have resulted in further stigmatization.  Such plans in and of themselves are not wholly problematic but they miss the fact that the people without disa
defaultbilities that people with whom 
defaultPWD
default interact may hold deeply ingrained stigmas against those 
defaultPWD
default. Simply providing formal work and educational opportunities to 
defaultPWD
default makes it easy for NGOs, microlenders, and development practitioners to continue to marginaliz
defaulte (via their expectations
default and ignoring of contextual issues
default) 
defaultPWD
default in these settings.  Likewise, stigma operates deep in the psyche and is often reinforced by language and ideology so that even development experts, NGO practitioners, and micolenders might pr
defaultesume that 
defaultPWD
default have not cultivated important educational expertise, knowledge, abilities, or practices that might already make them employable, able to pay back loans, begin businesses, and participate in their communities.  
